{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512773","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512773"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:00:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:00:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11948"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11948"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.18,0.34,0.04,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4544"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78138"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4544","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4544"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2022-08-04T17:51:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T14:18:16+10:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2022-08-31T20:33:51+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-17 02:13:21"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11948"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9435"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"342"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63560"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1307"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3406"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6754"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6772"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26788"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42690"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63560"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78138","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78138"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a three-month history of fatigue and weight gain. He has a medical history of gout, hypertension and chronic back pain. His medications include short courses of prednisolone for gout flares in the past year (two courses of two weeks each, inclusive of taper from 30 mg), perindopril, paracetamol and celecoxib. He does not take any complementary medications. On examination, his BMI is 35 kg/m2, and there are abdominal striae, acanthosis nigricans and hyperpigmentation of the palmar creases.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Iatrogenic Cushing\u0027s syndrome due to long-term steroid use","Cushing\u0027s syndrome due to ectopic ACTH production","Cushing\u0027s disease","Adrenal adenoma","Obesity class 2"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere is evidence of hypercortisolism, i.e. Cushing\u0027s syndrome, including weight gain, abdominal striae, fatigue and weight gain. Other symptoms and signs can include poor libido, emotional disturbances, moon facies and dorsocervical fat pad.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECushing\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct answer as only in ACTH-dependent Cushing\u0027s syndrome will there be the presence of hyperpigmentation due to the elevated levels of ACTH binding to MC1 receptors on melanocytes. It is also epidemiologically more common than other forms of endogenous Cushing\u0027s syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIatrogenic Cushing\u0027s syndrome due to long-term steroid use\u003C/strong\u003E leads to non-ACTH-dependent Cushing\u0027s syndrome where hyperpigmentation is not a typical finding. Both the dose and duration of steroids have bearing on the likelihood of developing side effects, and this amount of steroid is unlikely to cause such overt complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECushing\u0027s syndrome due to ectopic ACTH production\u003C/strong\u003E is a plausible option, though less likely. Ectopic ACTH production is usually due to secretions from tumours such as small cell lung cancer, medullary thyroid cancer and carcinoid tumours. These may be accompanied by constitutional symptoms including weight loss, fatigue, loss of appetite and night sweats. Hyperpigmentation is most commonly found with ectopic ACTH Cushing\u0027s syndrome, rather than with Cushing\u0027s disease. The presence of hyperpigmentation does warrant exclusion of ectopic ACTH given the cause may be malignancy. However, epidemiologically, Cushing\u0027s disease remains more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdrenal adenoma\u003C/strong\u003E is another non-ACTH-dependent cause of Cushing\u0027s syndrome. It is a benign tumour that secretes cortisol, if functional, and is treated with medications, surgical resection or a combination of both.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThough this patient does fall within the criteria of \u003Cstrong\u003Eobesity class 2\u003C/strong\u003E (BMI 35-39.9 kg/m2), this is a subset of a more complex underlying issue at hand which needs to be treated. Diet and exercise are important adjuncts to prevent further weight gain and muscle loss.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hyperpigmentation in a state of hypercortisolism is indicative of an ACTH-dependent cause for Cushing\u0027s syndrome.","Cushing\u0027s disease is the most common form of endogenous Cushing\u0027s syndrome, caused by a pituitary adenoma secreting ACTH."],"references":["Kairys N, Schwell A. Cushing Disease. [Updated 2022 Feb 2]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448184/","Chaudhry HS, Singh G. Cushing Syndrome. [Updated 2022 Jun 27]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470218/","Libianto R, Yang J, Fuller PJ. Adrenal disease: An update. Aust J Gen Pract. 2021 Jan-Feb;50(1-2):9-14. doi: 10.31128/AJGP-09-20-5619. PMID: 33543156. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33543156/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63560"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11948"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63560"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T14:17:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T14:18:33+10:30","number":7,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2025-01-09T14:18:06+10:30","plagiarismScore":0,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-4544-7.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250929%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250929T033019Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=5aff4d069a8ea99893fe60d39d0b3ee2e6977b2e5d73eb98d2877c42773124e8"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4544"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78138"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9435"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"